\v 3 \w They|strong="H5414"\w* \w cast|strong="H5414"\w* lots \w for|strong="H5414"\w* \w my|strong="H5414"\w* \w people|strong="H1818"\w*; \w they|strong="H5414"\w* \w traded|strong="H5414"\w* boys \w in|strong="H5414"\w* payment \w for|strong="H5414"\w* prostitutes \w and|strong="H8064"\w* girls \w to|strong="H5414"\w* buy wine \w to|strong="H5414"\w* drink.\f + \fr 3:3 \ft The point being made here is the casual way the victims were treated, and how little they were valued: being traded to buy a prostitute's services or some wine to drink. \f*
\p 
\v 4 \w Also|strong="H3068"\w*, \w what|strong="H3372"\w* \w have|strong="H3068"\w* \w you|strong="H6440"\w* got \w to|strong="H3068"\w* \w do|strong="H3068"\w* \w with|strong="H3068"\w* \w me|strong="H6440"\w*, Tyre \w and|strong="H3068"\w* Sidon, \w and|strong="H3068"\w* \w all|strong="H1419"\w* \w the|strong="H6440"\w* regions \w of|strong="H3068"\w* Philistia? \w Are|strong="H3117"\w* \w you|strong="H6440"\w* trying \w to|strong="H3068"\w* get \w back|strong="H2015"\w* \w at|strong="H3068"\w* \w me|strong="H6440"\w*? If \w you|strong="H6440"\w* \w are|strong="H3117"\w* trying \w to|strong="H3068"\w* pay \w me|strong="H6440"\w* \w back|strong="H2015"\w*, \w I|strong="H3117"\w* \w will|strong="H3068"\w* quickly pay \w you|strong="H6440"\w* \w back|strong="H2015"\w* \w what|strong="H3372"\w* \w you|strong="H6440"\w* deserve \w for|strong="H6440"\w* \w what|strong="H3372"\w* \w you|strong="H6440"\w*'ve done.
\v 5 \w You|strong="H3588"\w* stole \w my|strong="H3605"\w* silver \w and|strong="H3068"\w* \w my|strong="H3605"\w* gold \w and|strong="H3068"\w* \w my|strong="H3605"\w* best treasures, \w and|strong="H3068"\w* \w you|strong="H3588"\w* \w put|strong="H3068"\w* \w them|strong="H7121"\w* \w in|strong="H3068"\w* \w your|strong="H3068"\w* temples.
\v 6 You sold the people of Judah and Jerusalem to the Greeks so they could be sent far away from their land.
\v 7 But watch out! I will get them moving from the places you sold them to, and bring them back, and I will pay you back what you deserve for what you've done.
\v 8 I will sell your sons and daughters to the people of Judah, and they will sell them to the Sabeans, \w a|strong="H3068"\w* distant nation. I the Lord have spoken.
\p 
\v 9 Proclaim this among the nations: “Prepare for war!\f + \fr 3:9 \ft Literally, “Sanctify a battle.” Joel is presumably being ironic here. The same word is used in \xt 1:14\xt*\ft for calling a sacred assembly. \f* Call up the mighty warriors! Let all the soldiers get ready and advance!
\v 10 Hammer your plow blades and turn them into swords. Turn your pruning hooks into spears. Even the weak should say ‘I am \w a|strong="H3068"\w* strong fighter!’
\v 11 Hurry up and come, all nations from everywhere, and gather there.\f + \fr 3:11 \ft In the valley of Jehoshaphat, \xt 3:2\xt*\ft .\f* Bring down your warriors, Lord!
\v 12 Let the nations get ready, let them come to the valley of Jehoshaphat for there I will sit in judgment on all the nations.
\p 
\v 13 Start swinging the sickle, for the harvest is ripe. Come and tread the grapes for the winepress is full and the vats are overflowing because their wickedness has become so great.
\v 14 Huge mobs are in the valley of the Lord's verdict.\f + \fr 3:14 \ft The usual translation “in the valley of decision” suggests that these “multitudes” still are making their decision. However, this decision is that of God, and is the execution of that decision—in other words the verdict or sentence. \f* For the day of the Lord is near in the valley of his verdict.
\v 15 The sun and moon will become dark, and the stars will stop shining.
\v 16 The Lord will roar from Zion, shouting in \w a|strong="H3068"\w* loud voice from Jerusalem, shaking the heavens and the earth. But the Lord will shelter his people, protecting the people of Israel.
\v 17 Then you will know that I, the Lord your God, dwell in Zion, my holy mountain, and Jerusalem will be \w a|strong="H3068"\w* holy place forever, and no foreigners will ever march through her again.\f + \fr 3:17 \ft Referring to conquest by other nations.\f*
\p 
\v 18 At that time new wine will pour down the mountains, and the hills will flow with milk, and all the riverbeds of Judah will run with water. \w A|strong="H3068"\w* spring will flow out of the Temple and will water the valley of Shittim.\f + \fr 3:18 \ft Shittim means “acacia trees,” usually found in arid areas.\f*
\v 19 But Egypt will become desolate, and Edom \w a|strong="H3068"\w* desert wasteland, because of the violence they did against Judah, for in their land they shed innocent blood.
\v 20 Judah will be lived in forever, and Jerusalem for all generations.
\v 21 Will I pardon and leave unpunished the shedding of innocent blood? The Lord lives in Zion!”
\b
